  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Let <m>C</m> be the path given below from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m> with pieces <m>C_1</m>, <m>C_2</m>, and <m>C_3</m> as labeled. Let <m>\vF</m> be a vector field such that <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = 9</m>, <m>\int_{C_1} \vF\cdot d\vr = 6</m>,and <m>\int_{C_3} \vF\cdot d\vr = 7</m>.
      </p>
      <figure>
        <caption>An oriented path broken into three pieces</caption>
        <image width="60%" source="/scalarlineint_exercise2" />
      </figure>
      <p>
        Find the following:
        <ol>
          <li> <m>\int_{-C_3} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr} </m></li>
          <li> <m>\int_{C_2} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr} </m></li>
          <li> <m>\int_{-C_1-C_3} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr} </m></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-7</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-4</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>-13</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li> <m>\int_{-C_3} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr} =-7</m> because a change in direction will give the opposite sign for the dot product or line integral calculation.</li>
          <li> <m>\int_{C_2} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr}=-4 </m> because the the line integral of <m>C=C_1+C_2+C_3</m> is 9 but the line integrals of <m>C_1</m> and <m>C_3</m> sum to 13.</li>
          <li> <m>\int_{-C_1-C_3} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr}=-13 </m> because <m>\int_{C_1+C_3} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr}=13 </m> and <m>\int_{-C} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr}=- \int_{C} \vec{\vF}\cdot d\vec{\vr} </m></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
